    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1867-05-20T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1867-05-20T00:00:00-05:00" n="530" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d530">
                <head>
                    <persName type="from">Mr. Seward</persName> to <persName type="to">Mr.
                                Bancroft.</persName>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 2.]</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1867-05-20">
                            <hi rend="italic">May</hi> 20, 1867.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The only important unsettled question
                            between the United States and Prussia is that relating to the claim of
                            the latter to military service from citizens of the United States born
                            in that country, who may have left Prussia without performing the
                            service there required. The document<note n="*" xml:id="d530fn1">The
                                document referred to is Senate Ex. Doc. No. 4, 1st sess. 40th
                                Congress.</note> herewith communicated contains the most recent
                            correspondence upon the subject. You will notice in the latter pages of
                            the document the proposal made by Count Bismarck for a compromise of the
                            matter and my responses thereto.</p>
                <p>It is very desirable that this question should be equitably and
                            definitely adjusted. If Prussia should take that course, probably other
                            German states and possibly the governments of other countries would
                            imitate her example. This would be a great relief to a large number of
                            worthy citizens and to the government, which is bound to advocate their
                            rights and promote their interests.</p>
                <p>I am, sir, your obedient servant,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>WILLIAM H. SEWARD.</signed>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">George Bancroft,</hi> Esq., <hi rend="italic">&amp;c., &amp;c., &amp;c.</hi>
                    </p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
        </body>
